description.plain:
On “Blue Ain’t Your Color,” Keith Urban offers a fresh take on a classic sound. The song pairs sad-sack lyrics with a waltzing beat—nothing is more country than that. Also, there’s alcohol—another country trope that Urban folds into a modern-sounding composition. The song appears on Urban’s experimental ninth album, 2016’s ‘Ripcord.’ Urban says he didn’t want this song to sound like a “typical sonic presentation of a waltz.”

I wanted to try and mess with that a little bit, which is what drove the drum machine. Machinery drives the song, because you don’t normally have machinery in a waltz, unless you’ve got an organ.

Urban gave the song its “own sonic thumbprint” by experimenting with combinations of electronic drums and organic Telecaster guitar. He told the Boot it was a “very, very stark, minimalistic way of recording,” inspired by the classic country records of Don Williams. Urban had learned about Williams through his father, Bob Urban, who died during the making of ‘Ripcord’ and wound up influencing the record.

Urban is a fan of Williams’ “attitude”—the veteran Texas singer believes “the song is the picture, and the record is the frame.” Urban:


You’ve got to find the right frame, not too much and not too little, to make the picture really work.

So for the songs that don’t need much, like ‘Blue Ain’t Your Color,’ my dad’s record collection obviously has informed that a lot.

“Female” was written by Shane McAnally, Ross Copperman, and Nicolle Galyon, and performed by Keith Urban. The song was written around three weeks prior to its November 8, 2017 release and was inspired by the Harvey Weinstein sexual assault claims.

Songwriter Ross Copperman talked about the song in an interview at the 2017 BMI Country Awards stating,

We actually wrote a song three weeks ago called “Female”. It’s from the Weinstein announcement. We’re in a room and we’re like, ‘What can we do about this?’ And that’s the one thing we can do is write songs.

This song was Performed at the CMA-Country Music Awards

description.plain:
“John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16” is the lead single from Keith Urban’s ninth studio album. After hearing a demo of the song by songwriters Josh Osborne, Shane McAnally, and Ross Copperman, Urban previewed the song acoustically at the 2015 Country Radio Seminar to great listener feedback. He said the track “resonated deeply” with him immediately, thanks in part to the “the poetic use of the three Johns and what each represents to me.”

“John Cougar, John Deere, John 3:16” was sent to country radio on June 8, 2015, a day before its digital release.  Urban also performed the track live on the 2015 CMT Music Awards on June 10, 2015.

Cowriter Shane McAnally explained the meaning of the three Johns to Billboard:

John Cougar references all the sort of sexual tension of teenage angst all of us were growing up in. John Deere represents the way that our parents worked and what we saw living in the country, and of course [there’s] the element of religion. And [there’s] irony in John Cougar starting the line, and John 3:16 ending the line because that was the push and pull of that teenage thing.

description.plain:
Keith Urban’s new single “Coming Home” is progressive even compared to expectations he — one of country music’s most genre-expanding artists — has set. And still, Urban keeps it country by mixing the opening guitar riff of Merle Haggard’s “Mama Tried” into the song’s opening. It’s a savvy move that earned the legend a posthumous songwriting credit and received his family’s blessing.

The Urban co-written lyrics recall a universal need for the security that home and family provide. He knows this longing for his roots because he’s lived it; even surrounded by full skyscrapers, there’s a loneliness the 50-year-old can’t shake on “Coming Home.” Singer and songwriter Julia Michaels (who’s penned hits for many mega-stars) comes in, singing the sentimental bridge for this second single from the country singer’s upcoming 10th studio album:

Yeah I know it’s only one call away, but it’s not the same

The family of country music “home” songs just welcomed a most unusual cousin. Urban is not John Denver, and this song is not “Take Me Home Country Roads.” But, it’s a tune aimed at the next generation of country music fans — something the master songwriter has gotten better at with every passing year.

description.plain:
Written by Jaren Johnston, Jeffrey Steele and Tom Douglas, “Raise Em Up” is the January, 2015, single off Urban’s Fuse album. The track features backup vocals by Eric Church.

“Eric and I have been friends for a couple of years,” said Urban.

“I was hoping we could figure out a song to do at some point, and when ‘Raise Em Up’ came my way, I knew I’d found the one. I sent it to Eric and he loved it. Nathan Chapman and I created the track, Eric came down and we both sang, and it was all done in half a day!”

Written by Jaren Johnston, Jeffrey Steele and Tom Douglas, “Raise Em Up” is the January, 2015, single off Urban’s Fuse album. The track features backup vocals by Eric Church.

“Eric and I have been friends for a couple of years,” said Urban.

“I was hoping we could figure out a song to do at some point, and when ‘Raise Em Up’ came my way, I knew I’d found the one. I sent it to Eric and he loved it. Nathan Chapman and I created the track, Eric came down and we both sang, and it was all done in half a day!”

Like many of Urban’s recent vintage, this song showcases Urban’s soft, emotional lyric delivery, as well as what CMT.com called “a tiptoeing acoustic guitar.”

description.plain:
Keith Urban’s “Raining on Sunday” is actually a cover from 1999.

It was this version that became a major hit, though, as Urban released it as a single in 2003 with a music video that his fans still rave about to this day.

His desire to record “Raining on Sunday” came as a surprise to the original artist, Radney Foster.

He actually came up to me and said, ‘Man, I’m cutting “Raining On Sunday” off of See What You Want To See on my next record. I love that album.’ And you know I’ve heard that kind of loose talk before in this business. And I’ve learned not to take it too seriously.

As it turned out, Keith Urban was sincere, and it became one of his greatest hits.

description.plain:
“I Told You So” is the third song off of Keiths' album Love, Pain & the Whole Crazy Thing, it was released as the third single off that album.

“I Told You So” describes how Keiths' significant other told him that she wanted her space and that she wants to live her life without him for awhile. He meets her again by chance, and he tries to tell her that they are “better together” and that he won’t say “I told you so” when they get back together.

The song has a Celtic feel to it due to the use of the Uilleann Pipes.

description.plain:
This song describes a mans shame that he has for himself.

Its lyrics are confessional, with the narrator detailing his flaws and mistakes between chants of “shame on me, shame on me.” It is the only song on Fuse and one of few songs Urban has recorded in which there is only one vocal track, as opposed to the layered vocals and harmonies typical in his work, as the producers insisted the song’s message would come through more clearly with a stripped-down arrangement.
